Tutorial 2 - ThreeJS Coordinates and Camera Movement

Tutorial 2 - ThreeJS Coordinates and Camera Movement

10 steps

The trick to mastering ThreeJS is simple. You need to remember how to position your mesh in relation to your camera angle.

We will learn how to move our camera using our keyboards. This will be a great start to figure out the proper way to angle your camera. In fact, we will also learn on how we can add in a Panoramic Image that was taken from a 360 Camera. With the combination of a moveable camera and a Panoramic Image, we are able to create a Virtual Tour-like experience.

Click on this link to see what you can expect to build. You can interact with the page by pressing the following keys on your keyboard: W, A, S, D, Q, E, Left, and Right.

If this sounds interesting to you, get ready and open up your coding workspace as we zoom through the wonders of ThreeJS.

For technical help, be sure to join our StackUp Discord and head to the general-help channel.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

Introduction to ThreeJS
Upload content to Firebase, Netlify or Vercel via Command Line

Learning Outcomes

By the end of your learning, you will be able to

  • Move a mesh in relation to the camera
  • Listen to Keyboard Key events and change the behaviour of ThreeJS
  • Add a Panoramic Image to the scene
  • Learn about vectors and magnitude and apply it to a 3-Dimensional space

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 10

  • Step 1: Setting Up Our Workspace

    Now, go ahead and open your coding workspace of your choice. In our case, we will be using VS Code. Your workspace should open the root folder that we created previously, i.e. StackUp-ThreeJS. Once you have done so, open your terminal in your code editor and ensure that the current working directory is the root folder.

    Next, we are going to initialise our project with Vite. To get started with Vite, in our terminal, enter the following command you see below. 

    npm create vite

    Initialise with Vite

    The command above is to initialise the project with Vite. Once you have done that, you will be prompted to enter the name of the project. Enter threejs-city-fly in your terminal.

    Selection of Framework

    Once that is done, you will be asked to select the framework of the project you would like to use. In this case, select Vanilla and hit the Enter key. To select, use the UP ARROW key on your keyboard to shift the selection up, or the DOWN ARROW key on your keyboard to move the selection downwards. The item that is currently selected will be underlined.

    Choosing a Programming Language

    Once you have selected Vanilla, select JavaScript as our programming language. Then hit the Enter key.

    Once you have done the proper initialisation, run the following commands one by one in your terminal. 

    cd threejs-city-fly 
npm install three
npm run dev

    In the commands above, the first line will change the current working directory to the project directory we have initialised with Vite. Next, the second line will install the dependencies we need, in this project, we will need to have threejs installed. You might be wondering why it is install three instead of install threejs. This is because the package on NPM is called three.

    Lastly, the last command is to set up and run our local development server as we develop our web application. This local development server has a great benefit which grants us hot-reloading, which is the ability to see our code changes live.

    .

    Good to know

    As you host any JavaScript projects on Git services like GitHub, one of your folders in your project, node_modules will not be stored on your repository as it is ignored by default in your .gitignore file. Instead, the names, versions and other information will be stored in the package.json file.

    Each time when cloning the repository to your local machine, you will need to run npm install, which will reinstall all the dependencies your project need as listed in package.json (Please do not be confuse between package.json and package-lock.json)

  • Step 2: Sourcing for a 360 Image

    As technology advances, some cameras allow us to take a full 360 panoramic image. Not to worry, you do not need to have a 360 camera. You may go online to source for your own 360 image or you can use the one that is provided here.

    The example image is a 360 image. The image may look a little distorted but we will place this image into ThreeJS and ThreeJS will take care of the stitching to form a nice Panoramic image.

    Once you have sourced your 360 image, move the image to the public folder of your project. The public folder is where you can place all the media and assets you need for your website. Then, rename the image to image.jpg (or in any other image extension you have used).

  • Step 3: Index.html

    Now we will work on the structure of the website. Open index.html and replace the existing code with the code as shown below. 

    <!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Three.js City Fly Through</title>
    <style>
      body { margin: 0; }
      canvas { display: block; }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div id="app"></div>
    <script type="module" src="/main.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
    HTML

    In this web application, we will write internal CSS styling (lines 7 and 8). Next, we have an empty <div> element in line 12. That <div> element has an id, app. Later, in main.js we will add a renderer into this div. As such, we need to have an empty <div> element. Lastly, in the next line, line 13, we will add in a module script main.js.

  • Step 4: Creating Our Scene with ThreeJS

    We will now be working on the code that is responsible for initialising our scene on ThreeJS.

    Firstly, open the main.js file and replace the existing code with the code below. 

    import * as THREE from 'three'

var scene = new THREE.Scene();
var camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
var renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer();
renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);
    JavaScript

    In line 1, we will import the module three into our project. Using import * as THREE means that we will import all the files from three under the variable THREE. Next in line 3, we will create a new scene instance and add a new Perspective Camera, that will take on the full width and height of the website, into the scene as well.

    Once done, in line 7, we will append the renderer of ThreeJS to the empty <div> we have created in the previous step. We will query the element by the id of app.

  • Step 5: Adding Mesh to the Scene

    Within main.js, we will add the same cube that was added in the past tutorial. The cube will be a point of reference as we move our camera in subsequent steps. Add the code below in line 9.

    // Add a cube to the scene
var geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(1, 1, 1);
var material = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({ color: 0x00ff00 });
var cube = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, material);
scene.add(cube);

// Create a point light
const pointLight = new THREE.PointLight(0xffffff);
pointLight.position.set(5, 5, 5);
scene.add(pointLight);

// Create an ambient light
const ambientLight = new THREE.AmbientLight(0x404040);
scene.add(ambientLight);

// Set initial camera position
camera.position.z = 5;
    JavaScript

    In line 9 we will add a green cube to the scene. The cube's geometry is defined with a width, height, and depth of 1 unit each. In lines 16 to 17, we will create a point light with a white colour and positioned at coordinates (5, 5, 5) in the scene. This light will illuminate the cube and other objects in the scene.

    In lines 21 to 22, an ambient light is added to the scene with a dark grey colour (hexadecimal value 0x404040). This light provides overall illumination to all objects in the scene. Finally in line 25, the initial position of the camera is set along the z-axis at a distance of 5 units from the scene's origin. This will be the perspective from which the scene is viewed.

    If you want to check if you're on the right track with your main.js file, you may refer to the image below.

  • Step 6: Panoramic Image

    We will now work on adding the 360 image into our environment. In the same file main.js, add the following code below in line 27. 

    var loader = new THREE.TextureLoader();
loader.load('image.jpg', function (texture) {
  var sphereGeometry = new THREE.SphereGeometry(500, 60, 40)
  var sphereMaterial = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({
    map: texture,
    side: THREE.DoubleSide
  })
  sphereGeometry.scale(-1, 1, 1);
  var mesh = new THREE.Mesh(sphereGeometry, sphereMaterial);
  scene.add(mesh);
  mesh.position.set(0, 0, 0)
})
    JavaScript

    Important!: If your image name is different from image.jpg, please change line 28 accordingly. In the event, you do not see your image loading, please ensure that the 360 image is within the public folder. 

    In line 27, we will use the TextureLoader to load the image. The first argument of the .load() is the image path and the next argument is a callback function that will only be run once the texture is loaded. Once the texture is loaded, we will add a sphere and assign the 360 image to that sphere (lines 30 and 35). Lastly, we will set the sphere mesh to encompass the cube, the camera and the virtual lighting we have created, by defining the scale (line 34) and the position (line 37) of our mesh.

    You can refer to the image below to check if you have pasted the code correctly in main.js.

  • Step 7: Handling Keyboard Inputs

    In every HTML project, we can access the keyboard input that a user enters. Within the same file main.js, add the code found in this GitHub gist. Your file should now have 98 lines of code. You may refer to the image at the end of this step to see if you have added the code correctly.

    In lines 51 and 52, we listen for two events, keyup, and keydown. These two events will help us to determine how we control our camera. When the user first presses the key on their keyboard, JavaScript will receive a keydown event and that is when we can determine which key the user has entered (lines 43 to 45). Once we have done that, we store all the keys the user has pressed into an Object (line 41), with the value of true. Once the user has released the key, it will send a keyup event, and we will also determine which key the user has released and set the value of it to false on the Object. You might be wondering why we would save the event into an object. This is because the function "updateCameraPosition" can determine which key is active and apply the appropriate functions to respond whenever the key is pressed. You can think of the object as a circuit breaker, full of switches to determine where the key is pressed or not.

    For this, we will want to look for the keys: W, A, S, D, Q, E, Left Arrow, and Right Arrow. For starters, the WASD keys will be responsible for moving the camera Forward/Backward and Left/Right. Q and E will be to adjust the height of the camera, up and down. Lastly, the Left and Right arrows will adjust the rotation of the camera.

    Next, we need to determine the force and direction to move our camera. For example, for the camera to move forward, we can change the Z-Axis value. However, when we add the complications of rotating the camera, when the W key is pressed, instead of moving forward, we will appear to move backwards.

    As such in lines 58 and 62, we will need to apply a form of calculation to determine which is the right way to move the camera, given the rotation.

    Lets further break down the formula camera.position.z = new THREE.Vector3(0, 0, -0.1).applyMatrix4(camera.matrixWorld).z;

    new THREE.Vector3(0, 0, -0.1)

    This code creates a new THREE.Vector3 object with the coordinates (x=0, y=0, z=-0.1). This vector represents a point in 3D space, specifically in this case, a point slightly behind the camera along its negative Z-axis.

    .applyMatrix4(camera.matrixWorld)

    Here, the created THREE.Vector3 object (-0.1 units along the negative Z-axis) is transformed using the camera's matrixWorld. The matrixWorld is a transformation matrix that represents the camera's position and orientation in the scene. By applying this matrix to the initial vector, we are essentially transforming the vector to the camera's coordinate space.

    .z

    Finally, after the transformation, we extract the z coordinate of the resulting vector. This value represents the transformed z position of the initial vector in the camera's coordinate space.

    This concept is also applied to the rest of the directions as well, with the exception of the Upward and Downward movement. This is because when we rotate, it will rotate about the Y-axis, which will only affect the X and Z movements, leaving the Y-axis unaffected. Which is why in lines 78 and 81, we are able to simply change the value of the Y-axis.

    From lines 83 to line 88, we will change the rotation of our camera about the Y-axis.

    Lastly, from lines 92 to line 98, we request for animation frames. This code sets up a continuous animation loop using requestAnimationFrame(). The animate() function is called repeatedly, updating the cube's rotation angles to create a rotating effect. The renderer.render() call renders the updated scene on the screen, resulting in a smooth animation of a 3D cube continuously rotating around both the x and y axes.

  • Step 8: Building Our Application

    And that is it! Congratulations on making it to this point. Once we are satisfied with our project, it is time to build it for the web. What Vite will do is will compile the code base across multiple files into one HTML file. Open a new terminal and ensure the present working directory is the threejs-city-fly folder. Once you have done so, run the following command.

    npm run build

    This code will simply create a build of the application and place the build into a new folder called dist. Whatever is within this folder is the final product that can be now used in production. 

  • Step 9: Project Initialisation and Code Deployment (With Netlify)

    You can host your static site on Firebase, Vercel (instructions are in our Discord server) or Netlify. This tutorial provides instructions for Netlify only. You can choose one of the three web hosts, but do take note that deployment is via the command line interface.

    Firstly, we will need to install the Netlify CLI tool using the following command in your terminal:

    npm install netlify-cli -g

    You will also need to create an account on Netlify. Thereafter, ensure that you are logged in to Netlify on your browser.

    Next, we will obtain an access token so that you can deploy your project from your terminal. We will use the following command in your terminal:

    netlify login

    A new browser tab or window will be opened asking you to authorize Netlify CLI to access Netlify on your behalf. Click on the Authorize button. In the event that the browser tab or window is not opened, you can also copy the URL in your terminal and input it in your browser. Once authorization has been granted, your terminal should now have the message "You are now logged into your Netlify account!"

    Next, in your terminal, enter 

    netlify deploy

    You will come across the following prompts and these are the responses you should make:

    What would you like to do?: Create & configure a new site

    Team: <choose the default option>

    Site name: <yourusername>-threejs-city-fly (ensure you replace <yourusername> with your StackUp username)

    When asked to provide a publish directory, enter dist. Once the files have been uploaded, you will be provided with a "Website Draft URL". Go to that website and check that your website works as intended. You should see a green cube in the middle of the screen with a background image. You can try out the keys mentioned in Step 7 to see how the camera angle changes along the various axes. For example, pressing W will lead to the cube appearing larger.

    If everything looks good, use the following command:

    netlify deploy --prod

    Once again, you will be asked for the publish directory. Use dist.

    When you see the message "Deploy is live!" and your website URL is provided, you know that your site has been successfully deployed. Visit your website again and ensure that everything works well.

  • Step 10: Stacking It Up!

    You have reached the end!
